

SABLAY

   sabláy: blow with the fist

   sabláy: innuendo, indirect hint

   sabláy: speed and swiftness

   * sabláy: missed, didn’t hit the target, out of sync
     __________________________________________________________________

   As a verb, sabláy means to place a precious object like a piece of
   cloth or garment upon one’s shoulder as a gesture of respect. In
   Bikolano and many Visayan languages like Cebuano, Hiligaynon and Waray,
   their word sáblay can be translated into Tagalog as sampáy.

   The sablay draped across the body is part of the official academic
   costume of the University of the Philippines officially adopted in 2000
   after its first appearance in UP Diliman in 1990.

   Created by a group of professors from UP Diliman, the sablay is
   inspired by the malong of Muslim Mindanao, a loose garment made from a
   seamless bolt of cloth.
